ics, and its dramas of human choice.Quint shows how Milton radically revises the epic tradition and the Genesis story itself by arguing that it is better to create than destroy, by telling the reader to make love, not war, and by appearing to ratify Adam’s decision to fall and die with his wife. The Milton of this Paradise Lost is a Christian humanist who believes in the power and freedom of human moral agency. As this indispensable guide and reference takes us inside the poetry of Milton’s masterpiece, Paradise Lost reveals itself in new formal configurations and unsuspected levels of meaning and design.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEpic poetry, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aFall of man in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aAbdiel.  aAdam and Eve.  aAdam.  aAeneid.  aCatholic practice.  aChaos.  aCharybdis.  aChurch.  aCreator.  aDe rerum natura.  aDeath.  aEden.  aEpicurean cosmos.  aEve.  aGenesis.  aGod.  aIcarus.  aJohn Milton.  aLucretius.  aNicodemus.  aOdyssey.  aPandaemonium.  aParadise Lost.  aParadise of Fools.  aPhaethon.  aSatan.  aScylla.  aSin.  aTrojan War.  aUlysses.  aWar in Heaven.  abad choices.  acompanionship.  ademonic acts.  adevil.  adivine creation.  adivine light.  aenvy.  aepic tradition.  afallen angels.  afame.  aheaven.  ahell.  aheroism.  ahuman idolatry.  ahuman love.  aindividual recognition.  ainvisible Creator.  ainvisible God.  amarital love.  amilitary force.  amock-triumphs.  amonarchy.  anarrative.  aoracle site.  apagan rites.  apagan shrines.  apaganism.  apilgrimage.  apoem.  apoetic creation.  apoetic flight.  apoetry.  apower.  arebel angels.  asatanic fraud.  asocial deficiency.  aspiritual falsehood.  aspirit